 and the growing authority of paper matter. Both a wide-ranging literary analysis and a portrait of the age, Personation Plots reads canonical texts by Wilkie Collins, Mary Elizabeth Braddon, and Charles Dickens alongside several lesser-known sensation novels. The study, which anticipates debates over biometric identification practices in our own time, also features brief criminal biographies of two of the nineteenth century's greatest impostors, Alice Grey and Mary Jane Furneaux, and concludes with an afterword on imposture in the late-Victorian Gothic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFalse personation in literature. 0aFalse personationzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSensationalism in literature. 4aCriminology : Criminology. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : History of Science. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aFurneaux, Mary Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrey, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849085440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438490854423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438490854/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles